        <Document ID="AD107F76-1964-416F-8DD0-01B59C5A3060">
            <Title>About this Template</Title>
            <Text>TEMPLATE VERSION: V1.0.1
This project template shows how to combine Scrivener and the scientific and technical publishing system, Quarto. Quarto is basically an opinionated wrapper around Pandoc, including templates for multiple outputs alongside numerous filters and extensions. 

As I already demonstrate how to use Scrivener with pandoc, it was trivial to add a new workflow for supporting the use of Scrivener with the new technical and scientific publishing system, Quarto. Quarto bundles Pandoc along with a set of extensions and templates to provide an all-in-one experience, including Tufte-like output, extensive cross-referencing of equations tables figures &amp; code, and running code (R, Python, Julia, Dot, Mermaid etc.) to generate figures and complex layouts.

Because Scrivener supports Pandoc-flavoured markdown and automated post-processing, it also supports Quarto. However, for cross-referencing it places the labels at the end of the line, which conflicts with Scrivener’s block style injection of markup. A small mod of an existing pandoc-crossref post-processing script solved this problem. The script run from the post-processing pane of the Scrivener compiler runs quarto automatically after tweaking the path and fixing the cross-references.

Most features of Quarto can be enabled via three routes:

	1	Enabled using Scrivener styles — example: Callouts, Live Code. The only caveat is Scrivener doesn’t allow paragraph [block] styles to be nested.
	2	Enabled using Scrivener Section Layouts — example: Multipanel images / tables using cross-referencing attributes. This method enables nested blocks.
	3	You can always write plain markdown in the editor if you prefer…

Quarto’s documentation is excellent. Some of the cool features that Quarto includes:

	1	Panels with sub-figures and sub-tables.
	2	Based on Tufte, you can use margins for notes, figures, equations etc. Layout can be modified to span the page in many ways.
	3	Comprehensive cross-referencing, using Pandoc’s @citation markup (based on pandoc-crossref). For sub-figures / tables, it will add labels, like Figure 3(c) and these can be customised in th metadata.
	4	Academic author + affiliation metadata «similar to scrivomatic and pandoc scholar».
	5	Run Python, R, Julia code “live” to plot figures on each compile.
	6	Use graphing engines like Mermaid and Graphviz.
	7	HTML output has lots of cool tweaks, see https://quarto-dev.github.io/quarto-gallery/page-layout/tufte.html for example.
	8	Quarto allows installable extensions, so you can plug in new layout templates and code to extend its powers!


Quarto install almost everything required (you can use it to manage Pandoc, LaTeX, Graphviz, Mermaid and other tools all-in-one). For LaTeX it can install and update TinyTeX, allowing a small install footprint and automated addition of packages from CTAN.
</Text>
        </Document>
